#: ../lighting.rst:101
msgid "Activate"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:103 ../lighting.rst:114 ../lighting.rst:137
#: ../lighting.rst:164 ../lighting.rst:187 ../lighting.rst:210
#: ../lighting.rst:233 ../lighting.rst:268 ../lighting.rst:291
msgid "*Description*"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:105
msgid "The new ``Activate`` button turns on vertex normal editing mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:107 ../lighting.rst:118 ../lighting.rst:143
#: ../lighting.rst:191 ../lighting.rst:214 ../lighting.rst:272
#: ../lighting.rst:297
msgid "*Usage*"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:109
msgid ""
"You can just press ``Activate`` button while in ``Edit Mode`` and start "
"editing vertex normals. As it is active, object shading and its export "
"would be processed taking edited vertex normals into account. In other "
"words, after making some changes, this button should be left active if "
"you want to see the changes in the Blender Viewport and in the Blend4Web "
"engine."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:112
msgid "Show Normals"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:116
msgid ""
"This button actually duplicates the original Blender's button. It turns "
"on displaying the normals in the viewport, while the Size field allows "
"you to set their length."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:120
msgid ""
"You just need to push the Show Normals button either on the normal editor"
" panel or on the Blender's right panel in the Mesh Display section. You "
"can also set the convenient length of normals by tweaking the Size."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:135
msgid "Rotation"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:139
msgid "Using these instruments you can change direction of the normals."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:141
msgid ""
"The Rotate function is also available through the Shift+Ctrl+R hotkeys, "
"which allows rotation of vertex normals similarly to Blender."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:145
msgid ""
"Select one or more vertices that you want to edit and then rotate their "
"normals using the visual sphere or specify the direction as numerical "
"values."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:147
msgid ""
"The Rotate button provides a more convenient way to manipulate normals. "
"The rotation is performed in the screen space. Nevertheless, as with any "
"other rotations in Blender, you can isolate the desired axis during "
"rotation (by typing X, Y or Z)."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:162
msgid "Split Normals"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:166
msgid ""
"The ``Split Normals`` mode allows to edit vertex normals separately for "
"each ``face`` that form the ``vertex``. Index allows you to navigate "
"between the split normals."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:168 ../lighting.rst:237
msgid "Usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:170
msgid ""
"Turn on the ``Split Normals`` mode, select the vertex and change the "
"direction of its normals. Firstly, the normal which has the zero index in"
" the queue will be modified. Then, by switching between indexes you can "
"go to the next normal of this vertex and edit it, then to the next and so"
" on."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:185
msgid "Average Split"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:189
msgid ""
"The ``Average Split`` button averages the direction of the vertex normals"
" which was modified in the ``Split Normals`` mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:193
msgid ""
"To combine several split vertex normals into one, in order to obtain the "
"average direction of these normals, you just need to select the desired "
"vertex and press the ``Average Split`` button."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:208
msgid "Restore"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:212
msgid ""
"The ``Restore`` button restores the original direction of normals for the"
" selected vertices."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:216
msgid ""
"In order to restore the normal's direction to its original (which is "
"calculated on the basis of face normals), you need to select the desired "
"vertices and click the Restore button."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:231
msgid "Tree, Foliage and Face"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:235
msgid ""
"The ``Tree`` button directs the normals of the selected vertices away "
"from the 3D cursor. The ``Foliage`` button directs the normals of the "
"vertices strictly up. The ``Face`` button directs the normals of the "
"selected face parallel to the normal of this face."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:239
msgid ""
"In order to use the ``Tree`` function, select the desired vertices and "
"place the 3D cursor in the desired position. Then click the ``Tree`` "
"button so all the selected vertices will turn their direction away from "
"the cursor, as if they were shot from one point."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:241
msgid ""
"The ``Foliage`` function is very easy to use: just select the vertices "
"and press the button, so the function will direct their normals straight "
"up."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:243
msgid ""
"In order to direct the normals parallel to the face normal, just select "
"the desired face and click the ``Face`` button. The normals of the "
"vertices which form the face will be directed parallel to the face "
"normal. This function works only with one selected face at a time."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:266
msgid "Copy/Paste"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:270
msgid "Copies the normal direction from one vertex to another."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:274
msgid ""
"Select the vertex you want to copy from and click the ``Copy`` button. "
"Then, select the vertex you want to copy to and click the ``Paste`` "
"button. You may copy information from one selected vertex to many "
"different vertices. The buttons are not active in the ``Split Mode`` and "
"do not copy data of split vertices."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:289
msgid "Copy From Mesh"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:293
msgid ""
"This function allows you to copy the normals from one object to another. "
"There are two modes: ``Matched Vertices`` and ``Nearest Vertices``."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:295
msgid ""
"The ``Matched Vertices`` mode copies the normals from the vertices of one"
" object to another object's vertices only if they have the same "
"coordinates; the other vertices are ignored. The ``Nearest Vertices`` "
"mode copies the normals of the nearest vertices of the source object."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:299
msgid ""
"This function works in Blender's object mode. At first, you need to "
"select the object you need to copy from, then the object you need to copy"
" to. It is also necessary to select the target object's vertices to which"
" normals are copied."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:316
msgid "Lighting with Light Sources"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:318
msgid ""
"A scene can have multiple (but not less than one) light sources of "
"different types."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:322
msgid "Light source types"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:324
msgid "The following light source types are supported:"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:327
msgid "*Point*"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:327
msgid ""
"Light propagates from one point uniformly to all directions with gradual "
"attenuation."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:330
msgid "*Sun*"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:330
msgid ""
"Light propagates from an infinite plane in one direction without "
"attenuation."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:333
msgid "*Spot*"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:333
msgid ""
"Light propagates from one point within the angular limit, with gradual "
"attenuation."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:337
msgid "*Hemi*"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:336
msgid ""
"Hemispherical. Light propagates from an infinite hemisphere without "
"attenuation."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:340
msgid "Light source setup"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:342
msgid "Performed in the ``Object Data`` tab when a lamp object is selected."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:351 ../lighting.rst:473
msgid "*Color*"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:351
msgid "Light color. The default value is (1.0, 1.0, 1.0) (i.e. white)."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:354
msgid "*Energy*"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:354
msgid "Radiation intensity. The default value is 1.0."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:357
msgid "*Falloff*"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:357
msgid ""
"Attenuation type. The value is exported but the engine always uses "
"``Inverse Square``. It is applicable to the ``Point`` and ``Spot`` light "
"source types. The default value is ``Inverse Square``."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:360
msgid "*Distance*"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:360
msgid ""
"Attenuation parameter. It is applicable to the ``Point`` and ``Spot`` "
"light source types. The default value is 25.0."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:363
msgid "*Specular*"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:363
msgid "Create specular highlights. Enabled by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:366
msgid "*Diffuse*"
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:366
msgid "Do diffuse shading. Enabled by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../lighting.rst:369
msgid "*Spot Shape > Size*"
